  "voiceover": "Has the Qur'an really never changed a single letter? Muslims are often taught it's been preserved perfectly since Muhammad. The textual history is more complicated. There isn't one single Qur'an text in use today — there are several canonical readings, the qira'at. Most of the Muslim world uses the Hafs reading; much of North and West Africa uses Warsh; and the two differ in wording in places. And Islam's own most trusted source — Sahih al-Bukhari 4987 — reports that within a generation of Muhammad's death, the caliph Uthman standardised one version and had the others burned. That's hard to square with a text already perfectly preserved everywhere. This isn't said to mock a book Muslims love — it's an honest question. A claim of flawless, letter-perfect preservation only needs a few solid counter-examples to fall, and these are exactly that. And the deeper point: Christianity never rested on mechanical preservation in the first place. It rests on the historical evidence for the resurrection.",
